The paper deals with compressive imaging, which involves acquiring and reconstructing images from a small number of measurements. This is a topic that falls under several sub-categories of computer science, including information theory (cs.IT), computer vision (cs.CV), machine learning (cs.LG), multimedia (cs.MM), and signal processing (cs.SP). Given that the paper focuses on both the mathematical and practical aspects of compressive imaging, it is likely to be relevant to researchers in all of these areas. However, the emphasis on wavelet transforms and hidden Markov models suggests that cs.IT and cs.SP are the most likely sub-categories.
